<h6 class="kicker">Current Events</h6>
<p class="summary">Teaching ideas based on New York Times content.</p>
<ul class="refer">
<li><a href="/category/current-events/">See all in Current Events Â»</a></li>
<li><a title="See all Lesson Plans" href="/category/lesson-plans/">See all lesson plans Â»</a></li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Overview | </strong> How big of an issue is poverty in America today, and what are the most effective ways to address it? Is America still the great land of opportunity &#8212; where if you work hard and play by the rules, you can make it?</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">This week is the 50th anniversary of President Lyndon B. Johnson&#8217;s declaration of a war on poverty. Poverty and inequality have become a rising theme in our national discourse lately, with <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/07/25/us/politics/obamas-economics-speech-at-knox-college.html">President Obama&#8217;s speech</a> last summer decrying the &#8220;inequality of opportunity&#8221; and Congress&#8217;s recent <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/01/06/us/politics/popular-voice-in-the-capitol-its-the-popes.html">embrace of Pope Francis&#8217; message</a> about growing economic inequality. In this lesson students will learn about the problems of poverty and economic inequality in America and then will research possible solutions as they propose a new war on poverty for 2014.<br />
<span id="more-141142"></span><br />
<strong>Materials | </strong>Computers with Internet connection </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Warm-Up | </strong> We offer two Warm-Up options for this lesson. You may decide to do one or the other, or both:</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Option 1:</strong> Look at <a href="//www.nytimes.com/newsgraphics/2014/01/05/poverty-map/">this map illustrating the distribution of poverty</a> in the United States. Find your county, city or neighborhood and study both maps &#8212; the percentage living below the poverty line and the number living in poverty. (You can toggle between maps using the button in the top right corner of map.) How does your community compare with communities nearby?  How does it compare with the country over all? How does your state compare with other states?</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Or&#8230;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><iframe class="youtube-player" type="text/html" width="485" height="365" src="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QPKKQnijnsM" frameborder="0"></iframe></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Option 2:</strong> Watch <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QPKKQnijnsM">this video</a> about wealth inequality that went viral on YouTube in 2013. Before students watch the video, it is worth defining the terms &#8220;wealth&#8221; and &#8220;income.&#8221; Then, you may want to pause at intervals during the video to make sure students understand the points the filmmaker is trying to make. When the video is done, have students turn to a partner to discuss their reactions. Then discuss as a class. What does this video, and the data used in it, say about wealth inequality in America?   </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">As part of your discussion, you can point out some critiques of the data in the video and see if that changes students&#8217; reactions.  For example, this <a href="//www.forbes.com/sites/timworstall/2013/03/09/the-problem-with-the-wealth-inequality-in-america-video-it-commits-worstalls-fallacy/">Forbes magazine article</a> argues that the film neglects to take into account the effects of government programs, such as food stamps, Medicaid and free public education, that provide valuable services to millions of Americans. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The video is based on <a href="//www.motherjones.com/files/outofbalance.pdf">this chart</a> created by Mother Jones magazine using data provided by two professors at Harvard and Duke universities. If you or your students want more background information on the video, read this <a href="//www.motherjones.com/mojo/2013/03/great-american-inequality-video">Mother Jones article</a>.</p>
<hr/>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Related</strong> | In the news analysis <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/01/05/business/50-years-later-war-on-poverty-is-a-mixed-bag.html">&#8220;50 Years Later, War on Poverty Is a Mixed Bag,&#8221;</a> Annie Lowrey looks at the progress the United States has made in fighting poverty as well as the current debate about how the country should move forward. Have students read and annotate the article with a pen in hand, looking for evidence about the effectiveness of the war on poverty and possible solutions for addressing today&#8217;s problem of poverty.  </p>
<blockquote><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">
To many Americans, the war on poverty declared 50 years ago by President Lyndon B. Johnson has largely failed. The poverty rate has fallen only to 15 percent from 19 percent in two generations, and 46 million Americans live in households where the government considers their income scarcely adequate. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But looked at a different way, the federal government has succeeded in preventing the poverty rate from climbing far higher. There is broad consensus that the social welfare programs created since the New Deal have hugely improved living conditions for low-income Americans. At the same time, in recent decades, most of the gains from the private economy have gone to those at the top of the income ladder.
</p></blockquote>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Read the entire article with your class.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Questions</strong> | For reading comprehension and discussion:</p>
<ol>
<li>What evidence suggests that the government&#8217;s war on poverty has been a failure?</li>
<li>What evidence suggests the opposite &#8212; that the war on poverty has largely been a success?</li>
<li>What suggestions did you find in the article for further combating poverty?</li>
<li>What economic and sociological trends help explain why so many children and adults remain poor?</li>
<li>Why has economic growth generally failed to translate into income gains for workers over the past 30 years, according to the article?</li>
</ol>
<hr/>
<h4>A New War on Poverty</h4>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><webonly></p>
<div class="w190 right module">
<div class="entry">
<h5 class="kicker">RELATED RESOURCES</h5>
